Modifying \(Z_1\):

\[Z_1 W_1 Z_2 = \left\{ z_{1_j} w_{j,k} z_{2_k} \right\}\]

  • checking if using geometric or simple mean of \(z^2_2\) (second layer shrinkage) would help:

    • ztilsq_2 = \(\tilde{z}_2^2\); local shrinkage only
    • zsq_2 = \(z_2^2 = \tilde{z}_2^2 s_2^2\); including global shrinkage parameter for layer 2, \(s_2\)

Here, just checking to see if this would actually be any good as a correction (increasing separation, or mitigating effect of such small \(\tau\) since separation in \(\tilde{z}\) is already v. good)

resfiles <- c(resfile_pvtau1, resfile_pvtau2)
modfiles <- c(modfile_pvtau1, modfile_pvtau2)
zsq_means <- matrix(NA, nrow = length(resfiles), ncol = 2)
colnames(zsq_means) <- c("geom mean", "simple mean")
ztilsq_means <- z_means <- ztil_means <- zsq_means

for (sim_ind in 1:length(resfiles)){
  load(resfiles[sim_ind])
  nn_mod <- torch::torch_load(modfiles[sim_ind])
  
  ztilsq_2 <- get_ztil_sq(nn_mod$fc2)
  ztil_2 <- sqrt(ztilsq_2)
  ssq_2 <- get_s_sq(nn_mod$fc2)
  zsq_2 <- ztilsq_2 * ssq_2
  
  zsq_means[sim_ind, ] <- c(geom_mean(zsq_2), mean(zsq_2))
  ztilsq_means[sim_ind, ] <- c(geom_mean(ztilsq_2), mean(ztilsq_2))
  z_means[sim_ind, ] <- c(geom_mean(sqrt(zsq_2)), mean(sqrt(zsq_2)))
  ztil_means[sim_ind, ] <- c(geom_mean(sqrt(ztilsq_2)), mean(sqrt(ztilsq_2)))
  
}

  • the only version that would help is multiplying by the simple mean of \(\tilde{z}_2^2\), but Id have a hard time justifying it (why only the local shrinkage parameter from the 2nd layer?).

    • well, actually, maybe a justification would be as a correction to the 1st layers global shrinkage \(s_1\). But if anything, I would think dividing \(s_1\) by the geometric mean of \(\tilde{z}_2\) would make more sense ()

      • \(\tilde{z}_2\) are the local scale parameters in layer 2; the output of neurons in layer 1 get multiplied by these. If \(\tilde{z}_{2_j}\) is small, then the \(j\)th neurons output is shrunk. An argument could be made that the mean or geometric mean of \(\tilde{z}_2\) is a metric for how many 1st layer neurons retain relevance. 1) If the mean of \(\tilde{z}_2\) is \(\geq 1\), the layer 1 global scale param \(\tau_1\) is probably well-calibrated in relation to the number of neurons in layer 1 (proportion of included/total number of weights would be same). 2) if the mean of \(\tilde{z}_2\) is small (near 0), then \(\tau_1\) is likely smaller than it should be. Pursuing this in the next section:

Correcting \(\tau_1\)

Can we create a kappa-based metric for how shrunk \(\tau_1\) is? Dividing by mean \(\kappa_j\) from the next layer?

Actually, Piironen & Vehtari 2017 have a measure for the number of effective coefficients: \(m_{eff} = \sum_{j = 1}^{p} \left(1 - \kappa_{j} \right)\). We could take the \(m_{eff}\) generated by the 2nd layer (which does the same thing that the 1st layer does, i.e.horseshoe prior on coefs).

  • Then we could correct \(\tau_1\) by the number of neurons in layer 1 (\(d_1\)) divided by the effective number of neurons, i.e.corrected global scale parameter \(\tau_1^{corr}\) would be given by:

\[\tau_1^{corr} = \hat{\tau}_1 \times \left[ \dfrac{d_1}{m_2^{eff}} \right]\]

sim_ind <- 0
m_eff <- function(nn_layer){
  k <- get_kappas(nn_layer)
  sum(1 - k)
}
sim_ind <- sim_ind + 1
load(resfiles[sim_ind])
nn_mod <- torch::torch_load(modfiles[sim_ind])

ztilsq_1 <- get_ztil_sq(nn_mod$fc1) 
ssq_1 <- get_s_sq(nn_mod$fc1)
ztilsq_2 <- get_ztil_sq(nn_mod$fc2) 
ssq_2 <- get_s_sq(nn_mod$fc2)

zsq_1 <- ztilsq_1 * ssq_1
zsq_2 <- ztilsq_2 * ssq_2

zsq_1_tc <- zsq_1 * (16 / m_eff(nn_mod$fc2))^2
k_1_tc <- (1 + zsq_1_tc)^(-1)
err_mat <- err_by_max_bfdr(k_1_tc)$err_mat
err_mat[, 1:5] %>% 
  as_data_frame() %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = -max_bfdr) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = value, x = max_bfdr, color = name)) +
  geom_line() + 
  labs(
    title = paste0("tau_corr 1: sim ", sim_ind, ": FP/TP vs max_BFDR")
  )

zsq_1_tc2 <- zsq_1 * (16 / m_eff(nn_mod$fc2))
k_1_tc2 <- (1 + zsq_1_tc2)^(-1)
err_mat2 <- err_by_max_bfdr(k_1_tc2)$err_mat
err_mat2[, 1:5] %>% 
  as_data_frame() %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = -max_bfdr) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = value, x = max_bfdr, color = name)) +
  geom_line() + 
  labs(
    title = paste0("tau_corr 2 (sqrt): sim ", sim_ind, ": FP/TP vs max_BFDR")
  )

comments

My assessments of the plots:

  • Good: sim 1, 2, 8, 9, 11, 14

  • Acceptable: sim 4

  • early FPs, but roughly similar shape: sim 3, 5, 6, 12, 13,

  • bad: sim 7, 10, 15

  • also worth nothing that sims 1:5 were trained for 1M epochs, 6:15 for 500K epochs. Most appeared to actually do well starting around 125k epochs.

This seems like it is going to work. I do suspect that there may have been training issues in some of these whether under/overtraining since I just trained all of these for a fixed number of epochs (admittedly v. large), used the final epochs model/results, and only 1 model on each dataset. A common practice appears to be training several models on each dataset and using the one with the lowest training error; Rockova & Polson do this, for example).

\(\dfrac{d_1}{m_2^{eff}}\) or \(\sqrt{\dfrac{d_1}{m_2^{eff}}}\)?

  • Also, it might make more sense to correct \(\tau_1\) by the square root of \(\dfrac{d_1}{m_{eff}}\), i.e.:

\[\tau_1^{corr} = \hat{\tau}_1 \times \sqrt{ \dfrac{d_1}{m_2^{eff}} }\] - put into 2nd plots above.

diagnostics

good <- c(1, 2, 4, 8, 9, 11, 14)
meh <- c(3, 5, 6, 12, 13)
ugh <- c(7, 10, 15)

Looking at BFDR plots:

  • no sqrt:

    • bad: 15

    • OK: 2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 10, 12, 13

    • good: 6

    • excellent: 8, 9, 11, 14

  • sqrted:

    • bad: 15

    • OK: 2, 4, 8, 14

    • excellent: 3, 5, 6, 7, 9, 10,11, 12, 13

Using the square-rooted version makes more sense to me mathematically (since \(\tau\) is a scale parameter), and seemingly leads to better behavior (drastically reduces false positives, makes FP line much more concave, fdr and BFDRs tend to match up much better )
